---
/**
 * Problem/Solution Guide: Cryptocurrency Income Insurance
 *
 * Verifying income and qualifying for insurance when your earnings come from cryptocurrency, DeFi, or Web3.
 */

import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const title = "Insurance With Cryptocurrency Income: Verification Challenges and Solutions";
const description = "Cryptocurrency earnings create unique challenges for health insurance applications. Learn how to document crypto income, work with insurers unfamiliar with digital assets, and get coverage when your income doesn't fit traditional patterns.";

const tocItems = [
  { id: "overview", label: "The Verification Problem" },
  { id: "income-types", label: "Types of Crypto Income" },
  { id: "documentation", label: "Documentation Strategies" },
  { id: "insurer-attitudes", label: "Insurer Attitudes" },
  { id: "visa-requirements", label: "Visa & Income Requirements" },
  { id: "stability-concerns", label: "Income Stability Issues" },
  { id: "fiat-conversion", label: "Fiat Conversion Strategies" },
  { id: "best-practices", label: "Best Practices" },
  { id: "faq", label: "FAQs" },
];

const incomeColumns = [
  { key: 'type', header: 'Income Type' },
  { key: 'documentation', header: 'Documentation Options' },
  { key: 'verification_difficulty', header: 'Verification Difficulty' },
];

const incomeRows = [
  { type: 'Salary paid in crypto', documentation: 'Employment contract, wallet records, exchange statements', verification_difficulty: 'Moderate - employer verifiable' },
  { type: 'Trading gains', documentation: 'Exchange history, tax returns, accountant letter', verification_difficulty: 'High - no consistent income' },
  { type: 'DeFi yields', documentation: 'Blockchain records, portfolio tracking, tax documentation', verification_difficulty: 'Very high - complex to explain' },
  { type: 'NFT sales', documentation: 'Marketplace records, wallet transactions', verification_difficulty: 'Very high - irregular and speculative' },
  { type: 'Mining/staking rewards', documentation: 'Pool records, wallet deposits, tax filings', verification_difficulty: 'Moderate - predictable patterns' },
  { type: 'DAO compensation', documentation: 'DAO records, governance tokens, wallet history', verification_difficulty: 'High - unfamiliar to insurers' },
];

const strategyColumns = [
  { key: 'strategy', header: 'Documentation Strategy' },
  { key: 'approach', header: 'Approach' },
  { key: 'effectiveness', header: 'Effectiveness' },
  { key: 'considerations', header: 'Considerations' },
];

const strategyRows = [
  { strategy: 'Accountant verification letter', approach: 'CPA certifies income from crypto activities', effectiveness: 'High - professional verification', considerations: 'Need crypto-savvy accountant' },
  { strategy: 'Tax returns showing crypto income', approach: 'Official tax filings as income proof', effectiveness: 'High - government-verified', considerations: 'Requires compliant tax filing' },
  { strategy: 'Bank statements showing deposits', approach: 'Fiat deposits from crypto sales', effectiveness: 'High - familiar format', considerations: 'Need regular fiat conversions' },
  { strategy: 'Exchange account statements', approach: 'Balances and transaction history', effectiveness: 'Moderate - may not be understood', considerations: 'Some exchanges provide statements' },
  { strategy: 'Employment contract (crypto company)', approach: 'Traditional contract from Web3 employer', effectiveness: 'Moderate to high - depends on employer', considerations: 'Registered company helps credibility' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline="Insurance With Cryptocurrency Income"
  subheadline="You earn in Bitcoin, hold Ethereum, receive DAO compensation in governance tokens, or make your living from DeFi yields. When it's time to apply for health insurance, the underwriter asks for 'proof of income'—and traditional documentation doesn't exist for your situation. Here's how to bridge the gap between crypto earnings and insurance requirements."
  canonicalPath="/guides/cryptocurrency-income-insurance"
  tocItems={tocItems}
>
  <article class="prose max-w-none">

    <!-- Introduction -->
    <p class="lead">
      Your annual income is substantial—over $150,000 equivalent. But it comes from staking rewards, DeFi protocol fees, consulting paid in USDC, and occasional NFT sales. Try explaining that to a health insurance underwriter who wants bank statements and employment verification. The documentation gap between crypto-native income and traditional insurance requirements creates real challenges.
    </p>

    <p>
      This isn't about whether you can afford insurance. Crypto-wealthy individuals clearly can. It's about proving that income to insurers who operate in a traditional financial world. Insurance companies assess risk based on income stability and verification—and crypto income often fails their standard verification processes.
    </p>

    <p>
      This guide covers how to document cryptocurrency-based income for insurance purposes, which types of crypto income are easier or harder to verify, and practical strategies for obtaining coverage when your financial life doesn't fit traditional boxes.
    </p>

    <!-- The Verification Problem -->
    <section id="overview">
      <h2>The Verification Problem</h2>

      <h3>Why Insurers Ask About Income</h3>
      <p>
        Health insurers ask about income for several reasons. For income-rated policies, it determines premiums. For visa-required insurance, income verification confirms you meet visa requirements. For underwriting, income stability suggests you'll maintain coverage long-term. And income level often correlates with the coverage tier you're seeking.
      </p>

      <p>
        Insurers want to verify income, not just accept stated amounts. Traditional verification involves employer letters, bank statements, tax returns—documents that assume conventional employment or business income. Crypto income may not produce any of these in recognizable form.
      </p>

      <h3>The Documentation Gap</h3>
      <p>
        Traditional income creates paper trails: paychecks, bank deposits, W-2s or equivalent tax documents, employer records. Crypto income may exist only as blockchain transactions, DEX swaps, staking rewards, or token distributions—none of which look like traditional income documentation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Even when documentation exists, insurers may not understand it. An exchange statement showing $50,000 in monthly trading volume doesn't clearly show net income. DeFi yield farming records may be incomprehensible to underwriters. The gap isn't just missing documents—it's missing understanding.
      </p>

      <h3>The Stability Question</h3>
      <p>
        Beyond verification, insurers worry about income stability. Traditional employment suggests ongoing income. Crypto income—especially from trading or speculative activities—can be volatile. Last year's $200,000 could become this year's $50,000 or $500,000. Insurers pricing based on current income worry about future payment ability.
      </p>

      <p>
        This instability concern applies even when income is well-documented. A trader with perfect exchange records showing $300,000 last year still faces questions about whether that income will continue. Demonstrating income stability is as important as proving current income.
      </p>

      <h3>Regulatory and Compliance Factors</h3>
      <p>
        Insurance companies have compliance obligations—anti-money laundering, know-your-customer, regulatory requirements. Cryptocurrency income can trigger additional scrutiny. Some insurers avoid crypto-based income entirely rather than navigate compliance complexity. Others require enhanced documentation to satisfy their compliance teams.
      </p>

      <p>
        This isn't personal—it's institutional risk management. Insurers who can't verify income sources to their compliance standards may decline applications regardless of ability to pay. Understanding this dynamic helps you prepare documentation that addresses compliance concerns.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Types of Crypto Income -->
    <section id="income-types">
      <h2>Types of Crypto Income</h2>

      <ComparisonTable columns={incomeColumns} rows={incomeRows} />

      <h3>Salary in Cryptocurrency</h3>
      <p>
        Working for a Web3 company and receiving salary in cryptocurrency is the easiest crypto income to document. You have an employer, an employment contract, and regular payments—just in tokens rather than dollars. This looks most like traditional employment, and insurers can understand it.
      </p>

      <p>
        Documentation includes: employment contract (ideally stating salary value in fiat equivalent), regular wallet deposits from employer, exchange records if you convert to fiat, and tax filings showing employment income. If your employer is a registered company, they can provide verification letters just like traditional employers.
      </p>

      <h3>Trading Income</h3>
      <p>
        Active trading—whether crypto-to-crypto or crypto-to-fiat—produces income that's hard to verify and hard to predict. Trading gains vary dramatically. One year's profits may follow a year of losses. Insurers see this as unstable income, making coverage decisions difficult.
      </p>

      <p>
        Documentation options include exchange trading history, tax returns showing capital gains, accountant verification of trading income. But the volatility issue remains even with documentation. Trading income is verifiable but inherently unstable in insurers' eyes.
      </p>

      <h3>DeFi Yields and Protocol Income</h3>
      <p>
        Yield farming, liquidity provision, protocol fees—these generate real income but in ways completely foreign to traditional finance. Explaining to an underwriter that you earn income from providing liquidity to a decentralized exchange is challenging when they've never heard of DeFi.
      </p>

      <p>
        Documentation requires blockchain records (often needing interpretation), portfolio tracking service exports, and ideally accountant verification. The barrier isn't documentation existence—it's insurer comprehension. You may need to explain what DeFi is before explaining your income from it.
      </p>

      <h3>NFT Income</h3>
      <p>
        Artists, creators, and traders earning from NFT sales face the hardest verification challenge. NFT income is highly irregular—you might sell nothing for months, then sell a piece for $50,000. It's speculative, unfamiliar to insurers, and hard to project forward.
      </p>

      <p>
        Marketplace records (OpenSea, Foundation, etc.) show sales history. Wallet records show incoming ETH from sales. Tax filings capture reported income. But the irregular nature makes this income look unreliable even when well-documented.
      </p>

      <h3>Mining and Staking Rewards</h3>
      <p>
        Staking rewards and mining income can be relatively predictable—especially staking, which produces regular rewards at known rates. This predictability helps with insurance applications. You can show consistent income patterns even if the fiat value fluctuates.
      </p>

      <p>
        Document through staking pool records, wallet transaction history showing regular deposits, and exchange records for conversions. The regularity of staking income makes it easier for insurers to understand than trading or NFT income.
      </p>

      <h3>DAO Compensation</h3>
      <p>
        Working for a DAO—receiving governance tokens, grant payments, or streaming compensation—creates documentation challenges. DAOs may not issue traditional employment contracts. Payments may be in various tokens. The organizational structure may confuse insurers accustomed to corporate employers.
      </p>

      <p>
        Document DAO compensation through governance proposals showing your compensation, wallet records of token distributions, and conversion records. If the DAO has a legal entity, verification letters may be possible. Newer DAOs with informal structures make this harder.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Documentation Strategies -->
    <section id="documentation">
      <h2>Documentation Strategies</h2>

      <ComparisonTable columns={strategyColumns} rows={strategyRows} />

      <h3>Tax Returns as Primary Evidence</h3>
      <p>
        The strongest income verification is official tax returns showing your crypto income. If you're properly reporting crypto income to tax authorities, those filings become authoritative documentation. Tax returns are familiar to insurers and carry government verification weight.
      </p>

      <p>
        This assumes you're tax compliant—filing returns, reporting crypto income, paying taxes owed. If you're not (and many crypto holders historically haven't been), you lack this powerful verification tool. Getting tax-compliant isn't just about taxes—it creates the income documentation you need for insurance and other purposes.
      </p>

      <h3>Accountant Verification</h3>
      <p>
        A letter from a certified public accountant (CPA) or chartered accountant verifying your income carries significant weight. The accountant reviews your crypto records, verifies income amounts, and certifies their findings. This professional verification bridges the gap between crypto records and insurer understanding.
      </p>

      <p>
        Find an accountant experienced with cryptocurrency. They'll understand how to verify different income types and explain them credibly. An accountant who doesn't understand crypto can't effectively verify crypto income. The small crypto-specialized accounting community is growing—find someone in it.
      </p>

      <h3>Bank Statements Showing Conversions</h3>
      <p>
        Regular deposits from cryptocurrency exchanges to your bank account create traditional income documentation. Monthly deposits of $10,000 from Coinbase look like income to any insurer, regardless of the source. The conversion to fiat creates the paper trail.
      </p>

      <p>
        This strategy requires actually converting crypto to fiat regularly. If you hold everything in tokens, no bank statement documents income. Even if you prefer holding crypto, strategic conversions create documentation. You can always buy back if you want continued crypto exposure.
      </p>

      <h3>Exchange Account Statements</h3>
      <p>
        Major exchanges like Coinbase, Kraken, or Gemini provide account statements that show balances, deposits, withdrawals, and trading activity. These are more formal than blockchain records and look more like traditional financial documents.
      </p>

      <p>
        Not all insurers will understand exchange statements, but they're more accessible than raw blockchain data. Request formal statements (not just screenshots) that show your name, account details, and transaction history. These serve as supporting documentation even if not primary evidence.
      </p>

      <h3>Building a Documentation Package</h3>
      <p>
        Rather than relying on one document, prepare a comprehensive package: tax returns as primary evidence, accountant letter verifying income, bank statements showing fiat conversions, exchange statements showing crypto holdings, and employment contracts or DAO documentation as applicable.
      </p>

      <p>
        Include a cover letter explaining your income sources in plain language. Assume the underwriter knows nothing about crypto. Explain what you do, how it generates income, and how the documentation proves it. Make their job easier by connecting the dots.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA Box -->
    <CTABox
      variant="highlight"
      title="Find Insurance That Works With Your Income"
      description="Compare international health insurance options and find providers experienced with non-traditional income documentation."
      buttonText="Compare Plans"
      buttonHref="/best/expat-health-insurance"
    />

    <!-- Insurer Attitudes -->
    <section id="insurer-attitudes">
      <h2>Insurer Attitudes Toward Crypto</h2>

      <h3>The Range of Responses</h3>
      <p>
        Insurers range from completely unwilling to work with crypto income to fully accommodating. Some automatically decline applications mentioning cryptocurrency. Others treat it as they would any investment income. Most fall somewhere in between—willing to consider but requiring substantial documentation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Before investing effort in documentation, inquire about the insurer's stance. Ask whether they accept applicants with cryptocurrency-based income and what documentation they require. This saves time and frustration from applying to insurers who will decline regardless.
      </p>

      <h3>Brokers Who Understand Crypto</h3>
      <p>
        Insurance brokers experienced with crypto-native clients can guide you to receptive insurers. They know which companies accept crypto income, what documentation works, and how to present applications effectively. A knowledgeable broker is valuable when your situation is non-standard.
      </p>

      <p>
        Look for brokers serving digital nomads, tech entrepreneurs, or location-independent workers—populations with higher crypto income prevalence. They've navigated these issues before and know current insurer attitudes.
      </p>

      <h3>Smaller vs. Larger Insurers</h3>
      <p>
        Large insurers often have rigid underwriting processes that struggle with non-standard situations. Smaller, more flexible insurers may evaluate applications individually rather than fitting them into standard categories. For crypto income, flexibility often matters more than brand name.
      </p>

      <p>
        International health insurance providers focused on expats and digital nomads may be more accommodating than domestic insurers oriented toward traditional employment. Their client base includes more non-traditional income earners, so they've developed processes to evaluate these applications.
      </p>

      <h3>Evolving Attitudes</h3>
      <p>
        Insurer attitudes toward crypto are evolving. Five years ago, most insurers had no experience with crypto income. Now, some have developed specific processes. As crypto becomes mainstream, insurance industry accommodation will likely increase. But currently, expect extra friction.
      </p>

      <p>
        Keep trying if initially rejected. Different insurers have different standards. An application declined by one may be accepted by another. A broker can help identify appropriate options without repeated applications and rejections.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Visa and Income Requirements -->
    <section id="visa-requirements">
      <h2>Visa and Income Requirements</h2>

      <h3>Digital Nomad Visas and Crypto</h3>
      <p>
        Many digital nomad visas require proof of minimum income—$2,000/month, $50,000/year, or similar. These requirements were designed for remote workers with traditional employment. Crypto income creates the same documentation challenges for visa applications as for insurance.
      </p>

      <p>
        Visa requirements often specify "remote work" or "self-employment"—categories where crypto income might fit. But income verification requirements may assume traditional documentation. Research specific visa requirements and whether crypto income is accepted before committing to an application.
      </p>

      <h3>Insurance Requirements for Visas</h3>
      <p>
        Some visas require health insurance as a condition. If insurance applications fail due to income verification issues, it affects visa eligibility—a cascading problem. Address insurance documentation early in visa planning to avoid this trap.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some countries are more flexible about income verification for visas than private insurers are. Government requirements may be satisfied with tax returns or bank statements even when insurers want more. Research both sets of requirements.
      </p>

      <h3>Establishing Local Presence</h3>
      <p>
        In some countries, establishing local residence provides access to public healthcare regardless of income documentation. This sidesteps insurance income verification entirely. Understanding residency pathways and healthcare access may offer solutions when private insurance proves difficult.
      </p>

      <p>
        Local insurance in some countries has simpler requirements than international health insurance. While coverage may be limited, it may meet visa requirements and provide basic protection while you work on better documentation for comprehensive coverage.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Income Stability Concerns -->
    <section id="stability-concerns">
      <h2>Addressing Income Stability Concerns</h2>

      <h3>Demonstrating Consistent Income</h3>
      <p>
        Even with good documentation, insurers worry about crypto income stability. Address this proactively. Show multiple years of income if possible—three years of consistent six-figure crypto income is more convincing than one year. Show the pattern, not just the current snapshot.
      </p>

      <p>
        Explain how your income is generated and why it's likely to continue. Staking rewards from a significant holding are more predictable than trading gains. Protocol income from established DeFi projects is more stable than speculative NFT sales. Frame your income in terms of its reliability.
      </p>

      <h3>Asset Backing</h3>
      <p>
        Even if current income varies, substantial crypto holdings suggest ability to pay premiums. If you hold $500,000 in cryptocurrency, you can clearly afford a $15,000 annual insurance premium regardless of this year's income. Assets demonstrate financial stability beyond current income.
      </p>

      <p>
        Document holdings through exchange balances, wallet balances, and portfolio summaries. While not income proof, asset documentation supports your application by showing financial stability and premium payment ability.
      </p>

      <h3>Diversified Income Sources</h3>
      <p>
        If your crypto income comes from multiple sources—staking, consulting, trading—document the diversification. Multiple income streams are more stable than single sources. If trading declines, consulting might increase. Diversification suggests resilience.
      </p>

      <p>
        Traditional income alongside crypto income strengthens applications further. If you have rental income, dividends, or any traditional income sources, include them. Combined income from multiple sources—some traditional, some crypto—looks more stable than crypto alone.
      </p>

      <h3>Pre-Paying Premiums</h3>
      <p>
        Offering to pre-pay premiums—quarterly or annually rather than monthly—demonstrates ability to afford coverage and reduces insurer risk. If income stability is the concern, removing payment risk by pre-paying addresses it directly.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some insurers prefer annual payment anyway, offering discounts for upfront payment. Proposing this approach signals financial stability and removes monthly payment default risk from the insurer's concerns.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Fiat Conversion Strategies -->
    <section id="fiat-conversion">
      <h2>Fiat Conversion Strategies</h2>

      <h3>Creating Traditional Documentation</h3>
      <p>
        The simplest solution to documentation problems is converting enough crypto to fiat to create traditional bank records. Monthly fiat deposits document income in a format every insurer understands. This doesn't require liquidating your entire portfolio—just enough to document income.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you earn equivalent of $10,000 monthly in crypto, converting $10,000 monthly to fiat creates bank statements showing $10,000 monthly deposits. You can reinvest if you prefer crypto exposure—the conversion creates documentation regardless of what you do afterward.
      </p>

      <h3>Stablecoin Strategies</h3>
      <p>
        Receiving or converting income to stablecoins (USDC, USDT, DAI) provides price stability even before fiat conversion. Stablecoin holdings are easier to value and explain than volatile tokens. Regular stablecoin income shows consistency without fiat volatility.
      </p>

      <p>
        Some exchanges provide statements specifically showing stablecoin deposits and holdings. These function like fiat statements in terms of clarity, even though they're still on-chain assets. Stablecoins bridge the gap between volatile crypto and traditional fiat.
      </p>

      <h3>Strategic Conversion Timing</h3>
      <p>
        Plan fiat conversions around documentation needs. If you're applying for insurance in three months, establish a pattern of monthly conversions now. Twelve months of bank deposits is more convincing than two months. Build documentation history before you need it.
      </p>

      <p>
        Regular conversion patterns also demonstrate discipline and income stability. Erratic conversions—nothing for months, then a large sum—look less stable than consistent monthly conversions even if the total is similar.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Best Practices -->
    <section id="best-practices">
      <h2>Best Practices</h2>

      <h3>Be Tax Compliant</h3>
      <p>
        Tax compliance creates the most authoritative income documentation. File returns, report crypto income, pay taxes owed. This creates government-verified records that insurers trust. Tax compliance isn't just legal obligation—it's essential documentation.
      </p>

      <p>
        Work with a crypto-specialized accountant to ensure proper reporting. Different income types have different tax treatments. Getting this right creates clean documentation; getting it wrong creates problems beyond just insurance.
      </p>

      <h3>Use a Crypto-Savvy Broker</h3>
      <p>
        An insurance broker experienced with crypto clients can navigate these challenges for you. They know which insurers to approach, what documentation works, and how to present applications. Their expertise saves time and improves outcomes.
      </p>

      <p>
        A good broker can also push back on insurer concerns, explain your situation effectively, and advocate for your application. This advocacy matters when your situation doesn't fit standard underwriting categories.
      </p>

      <h3>Document Everything</h3>
      <p>
        Maintain comprehensive records of all crypto income. Track every transaction, keep exchange statements, use portfolio tracking services. When documentation is needed, you want to produce it quickly, not reconstruct it from incomplete records.
      </p>

      <p>
        Create documentation packages in advance. Even before you need insurance, compile your income documentation. This preparation means you can apply efficiently when the time comes, rather than scrambling to gather records.
      </p>

      <h3>Explain Proactively</h3>
      <p>
        Don't wait for underwriters to be confused. Proactively explain your income sources, provide context, and connect documentation to income claims. A cover letter explaining your situation in plain English helps underwriters understand what they're seeing.
      </p>

      <p>
        Assume zero crypto knowledge. Explain what staking is, what a DEX is, how DeFi generates income. Make the underwriter's job easy by providing context. The easier you make it to understand your application, the better your chances.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Will insurers decline me because I earn in cryptocurrency?</h3>
      <p>
        Some will, but many won't—especially international health insurers serving digital nomads and location-independent workers. The key is adequate documentation and finding insurers experienced with non-traditional income. Expect more friction than traditional income but not automatic rejection.
      </p>

      <h3>What's the minimum documentation I need?</h3>
      <p>
        At minimum, tax returns showing crypto income and bank statements showing fiat conversions. An accountant letter significantly strengthens the application. The more documentation you provide, the better your chances with skeptical underwriters.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I just claim a lower income to avoid verification hassle?</h3>
      <p>
        Don't understate income—this can constitute insurance fraud if discovered. Some policies are income-rated, and understating income to get lower premiums creates risk. Be accurate; address verification challenges through documentation, not misrepresentation.
      </p>

      <h3>What if I don't have tax returns because I haven't been filing?</h3>
      <p>
        This is a bigger problem than insurance. Get tax compliant—both for legal reasons and to create documentation. Work with an accountant to file back taxes if needed. Future compliance creates future documentation; past non-compliance limits current options.
      </p>

      <h3>Are there insurers that specifically accept crypto income?</h3>
      <p>
        Few insurers explicitly market to crypto holders, but some are known to be more flexible—often those serving digital nomads, expats, and location-independent workers. A broker serving this demographic can identify current-best options.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I pay insurance premiums in cryptocurrency?</h3>
      <p>
        Very few insurers accept crypto payment directly. Most require fiat payment. This is separate from income verification—even if your income is crypto, you'll likely need to convert to fiat to pay premiums. A few crypto-native companies are emerging, but options remain limited.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Closing -->
    <section>
      <h2>Bridging the Documentation Gap</h2>
      <p>
        Cryptocurrency income is real income—often substantial income. The challenge isn't legitimacy; it's documentation in formats that traditional institutions understand. As more people earn through crypto, systems will adapt. Until then, you need to bridge the gap yourself.
      </p>

      <p>
        The strategies in this guide—tax compliance, accountant verification, strategic fiat conversion, comprehensive documentation—create that bridge. They translate your crypto-native income into language insurers understand. The effort required is real but surmountable.
      </p>

      <p>
        Don't let documentation challenges prevent you from getting proper health insurance. The extra work to document crypto income is worthwhile when it means comprehensive coverage for you and your family. Make the system work for your situation—it just requires more intentional documentation than traditional income.
      </p>
    </section>

  </article>
</PageShell>
